This is a known breaking change. Android 15 (API 35) — which .NET 10 targets — makes apps **edge-to-edge by default** and ignores `SOFT_INPUT_ADJUST_RESIZE`. The fix is to react to **IME window insets** instead.

### Recommended fix

In your `Platforms/Android/MainActivity.cs`, override `OnCreate` and attach an insets listener that adjusts bottom padding when the keyboard appears:

```csharp
using Android.Views;
using AndroidX.Core.View;
using Microsoft.Maui.Controls.Compatibility.Platform.Android;

protected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)
{
    base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);

    if (Window?.DecorView is { } decorView)
    {
        ViewCompat.SetOnApplyWindowInsetsListener(decorView, new ImeInsetsListener());
    }
}

private class ImeInsetsListener : Java.Lang.Object, IOnApplyWindowInsetsListener
{
    public WindowInsetsCompat OnApplyWindowInsets(Android.Views.View v, WindowInsetsCompat insets)
    {
        var imeInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.Ime());
        var navBar   = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.NavigationBars());

        // Use the larger of keyboard or nav-bar bottom inset
        int bottom = Math.Max(imeInsets.Bottom, navBar.Bottom);
        v.SetPadding(v.PaddingLeft, v.PaddingTop, v.PaddingRight, bottom);

        return insets;
    }
}
```

### Why this works

| .NET 9 / API 34 | .NET 10 / API 35 |
|---|---|
| `adjustResize` shrinks the window | `adjustResize` is a **no-op** |
| System handles layout shift | You must consume `Ime()` insets yourself |

### Tips

- **Remove** any `WindowSoftInputModeAdjust.Resize` calls — they do nothing now.
- In your XAML, keep your input bar at the bottom of a `Grid`; the padding shift will push it up automatically.
- If you also need iOS handling, iOS `KeyboardAutoManager` in MAUI still works — this change is Android-only.
